Japan's "Financial Sanctions" against DPRK Assailed 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Pyongyang, September 25 (KCNA) -- Rodong Sinmun Monday ridicules Japan's application of "financial sanctions" against the DPRK as a farce of a jester of a circus troupe.
 The Japanese authorities, bereft of reason, are foolishly performing short-sighted and senseless buffoonery reminding us of a rural vendor, regarding "financial sanctions" as "a panacea," says a Rodong Sinmun commentary Monday. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The analyst goes on: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Japan's "financial sanctions" do not surprise the DPRK at all. But the DPRK has to say a caustic word about Japan's mean racket of "financial sanctions." &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Dancing to other's tune, Japan is attempting to pressurize and strangle the DPRK with such "financial sanctions" to drive it somewhere. It is, however, a poor, third-rate diplomacy of bat-blind philistines. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Japan is whipping itself into senseless frenzy to please the whim of its American master. It is acting flippantly not to fall behind the U.S. in the racket of sanctions against the DPRK. It does not warrant surprise, considering that Japan has made it its physical quality to lick the boots of the American master and tail behind the U.S. It is unseemly for Japan, styling itself "a big power," to behave like this. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Japan's noisy row of "financial sanctions" against the DPRK is a disgusting behavior of a slovenly political charlatan bent on refurbishing his public image by ingratiating himself with his American master and feathering his own nest by following the U.S. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Japan's clumsy and wicked act is a perfidy trampling upon the spirit and requirements of the DPRK-Japan Pyongyang Declaration. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 It is an utterly unreasonable sophism to describe the application of the "financial sanctions" as "a catalyzer" for "dialogue." It is a folly rendering the problem more complicated and carrying the DPRK-Japan confrontation to extremes. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 It is justifiable and natural for the DPRK to put up a tough rebuff to Japan's desperate political provocation. The situation is very serious and the consequences are unpredictable. Japan would be well advised to behave with discretion, pondering over the serious consequences to be entailed by its harebrained act against the DPRK.

State Commendations and Gifts Awarded to FIFA U-20 Championship Winners 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Pyongyang, September 25 (KCNA) -- A ceremony of awarding state commendations and gifts to young women footballers, coaches and officers concerned who came first in the third FIFA U-20 Women's World Championship was held at the April 25 House of Culture Monday.
 Yang Hyong Sop, vice-president of the Presidium of the Supreme People's Assembly, in his address said that Kim Jong Il bestowed high honor upon young women footballers and presented them with such gifts which they would hand down through generations as deluxe cars and buses and flats. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 At the ceremony the title of Labor Hero of the DPRK and Gold Medal (Hammer and Sickle) and National Flag Order First Class were conferred on Hong Myong Gum of the Amnokgang Sports Group and 18 others, wristwatches bearing the august name of President Kim Il Sung upon Kim Kyong Hwa of the April 25 Sports Group and 26 others and "Kim Il Sung Youth Honor Prize" upon Jong Ryon Hui of the April 25 Sports Group and 4 others. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The title of People's Sportsman was awarded to Kim Song Hui of the Pyongyang City Sports Group and 17 others and the title of Merited Sportsman to Ri Jin Hui of the Rimyongsu Sports Group and 5 others. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Gifts sent by Kim Jong Il to coach of the Pyongyang City Sports Group Choe Kwang Sok were conveyed to them. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Choe Kwang Sok and Hong Myong Gum, heroes of labor and people's sportspersons, and other speakers noted that they were deeply touched by the profound benevolence of Kim Jong Il who highly estimated their success as a great patriotic deed, though it was a modest one made in the course of fulfilling their commitment, and put forward them as hero footballers. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 They evinced their resolution to win every game they will play by displaying the transparent spirit of devotedly defending the leader and the spirit of defending the country and the spirit of waging dynamic ideological and fighting spirit battles, speed campaign and technical battle as befitting sportspersons of Songun Korea and thus strikingly demonstrate the dignity and honor of Kim Il Sung's nation and uphold Kim Jong Il's Songun revolutionary leadership with gold medals. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Present at the ceremony were Kim Jung Rin, secretary of the Central Committee of the Workers' Party of Korea, Kwak Pom Gi, vice-premier of the Cabinet, and others.

Spain-based Friendly Organization Introduces Korea 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Pyongyang, September 25 (KCNA) -- The Spain-based Association for Friendship with Korea newly posted several articles and photos on Internet homepage "One Korea Network."
 An article titled "Essence of Songun Politics" said that the Songun politics pursued by the Workers' Party of Korea helps reliably defend the country, the revolution and socialism and push forward socialist construction as a whole with the Korean People's Army as its main force. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Another article titled "Anti-U.S., Mindset of South Korean People" noted that the U.S. troops present in south Korea who had been regarded as "liberator" and "supporter" are branded as "forces obstructive to reunification" and "shock brigade in implementing colonial policy" and the U.S. is denounced as the principal culprit threatening peace of the Korean Peninsula. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Another article titled "National Independence and Korea's Reunification" said that a dramatic change has been brought about in accomplishing the Korean nation's cause of reunification after the publication of the June 15 North-North Joint Declaration. What is noticeable in particular is that anti-U.S. sentiment is rapidly mounting in south Korea where the idea of worship and fear of America had been predominant for several decades, it stressed.

Russian People's Actor on Impressions of Korea Visit 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Pyongyang, September 25 (KCNA) -- Josif Kobzon, chairman of the Cultural Committee of the State Duma of the Russian Federation who is winner of the Soviet State Prize and people's actor, dedicated a travelogue headlined "I was completely fascinated by Comrade Kim Jong Il" to the paper "Zolotoi Log" on Sept. 19.
 The author pointed out that many things of Korea startled him. One of them, he said, is Korean people's culture, life and patriotism. There are no prostitutes and drug addicts in Korea, he said, and went on: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 My inspection of Pyongyang Kim Won Gyun Conservatory, the Mangyongdae Schoolchildren's Palace and other places brought home to me what a great concern is paid to the younger generation in Korea. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Natural landscape is also wonderful. In a nutshell, Pyongyang is like an earthly paradise. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Kim Jong Il knows well about Russian culture, which moved me completely.

Branch Offices of Government Employees' Union in S. Korea Forcibly Closed 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Pyongyang, September 25 (KCNA) -- South Korean authorities mobilized police to forcibly close branch offices of the "National Government Employees' Union" on Sept. 22, according to south Korean MBC.
 The "government" authorities took the union to task for recently struggling in demand of a stop to the south Korea-U.S. joint military exercises "Ulji Focus Lens" and branded the union as an "illegal organization" as it does not recognize the "law on government employees' union." And the authorities have threatened that they would forcibly close those branch offices which did not give a notification of their establishment in case of failing to disestablish them by themselves. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Unable to bring the unionists to their knees with threat and blackmail, the authorities drove police forces out to close the offices forcibly under the pretext of "administrative execution" that day. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The police went to at least 110 branch offices of more than 140 offices which did not give notification and forcibly drove unionists out of them and put the seal on office rooms. The police took away at least 50 unionists on the charge of "interference with government officials in the execution of their duties." &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The south Korean authorities' reckless suppression invited great protest from among unionists and people of different social standings. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The employees' union called a press conference in protest against the authorities' reckless action at the Citizen's Park of Kwanghwamun in Seoul. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Unionists of branches in Pusan, Ulsan, South Kyongsang Province and other places of south Korea fiercely fought against the police to defend their offices. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Meanwhile, 203 lawyers held a press conference in front of the "government" building in Seoul on the same day and demanded the authorities stop the moves to close branch offices, aimed to stamp out the employees' union.

Reasonable Solution to Registration Fee Raise Urged in S. Korea 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Pyongyang, September 25 (KCNA) -- The "National Measure Committee for Student Education" of south Korea reportedly called a press conference in front of the building of the "National Assembly" in Seoul on Sept. 20, at which it demanded a reasonable solution to the issue of the raise of registration fees by the authorities.
 Speakers at the press conference lamented that the registration fees of university students rose every year due to the unjustifiable educational opening policy of the "government." The "National Assembly" should put forward a measure for a reasonable solution to the issue at an early date so that university students may study with a sense of relief, they said. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 A statement read out at the press conference called upon all the university students to turn out all at once in protest against the raise of registration fees and the scheme to revise the "law on private schools." &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 At the end of the press conference the participants handed to the "National Assembly" a letter of protest demanding the institution of a system for the solution of the problem of registration fees, a stop to the moves to revise the "law on private schools," opening to the public of the content of the negotiation for educational opening and so on.

Animal Museum of Central Zoo in DPRK
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Pyongyang, September 25 (KCNA) -- There is the Animal Museum in the Central Zoo, which is inhabited by rare animals presented to Kim Jong Il by Jonas Wahlstrom, director of the Skansen Aquarium in Sweden.
 The museum, which was open to the public on October Juche 74 (1985), consists of aquariums and quarters for reptiles, small monkeys and nocturnal animals. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 One thousand and hundreds of fishes of more than sixty species including Arowana and Spotted Indian Knife live in the aquariums and reptiles including Cuban Crocodiles and Indian Boas in the reptile quarter. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 In the quarter for small monkeys which makes the visitors feel as if they were in forests of coconut, larch and oak trees, they can see scores of monkeys including Common Marmoset, Pygmy Marmoset and Squirrel Monkey. Among them are rare monkeys each of which weighs 120 grams. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The quarter for nocturnal animals houses tens of animals of five species such as Lesser Bush Baby, Indian Flying Fox and Hedgehog. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Working people and school youth and children have a pleasant time, seeing animals associated with meaningful stories.

Second Pyongyang Autumn International Trade Fair Opens
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Pyongyang, September 25 (KCNA) -- An opening ceremony of the Second Pyongyang Autumn International Trade Fair was held at the Three Revolution Exhibition on Monday. 
 Present at the ceremony were Vice-Premier of the Cabinet Ro Tu Chol, Minister of Foreign Trade Rim Kyong Man, officials concerned, delegations and delegates of the DPRK, foreign countries and regions, foreign diplomatic envoys and staff members of foreign embassies. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Jo Jong Ho, vice-minister of Foreign Trade, made a congratulatory speech at the ceremony. Then followed an opening address of Kim Tong Myong, director of the Korean International Exhibition Corporation. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The speakers said that the fair will be an important occasion in strengthening friendly relations and further developing economic cooperation and exchanges among different countries. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Participants put bouquets and made a bow before a photograph of President Kim Il Sung standing together with Kim Jong Il in the venue. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 And they looked round up-to-date machine tools, newly developed medicines and other diverse products, video shows and information materials introducing different companies and products presented by the DPRK, China, Indonesia, Switzerland, Britain, Thailand, Italy, Belarus and Hong Kong of China. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 A reception was given in connection with the opening of the fair in the evening. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The fair continues till Sept. 28.
